<pretext>
    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="sec-VIII-6-sols">
        <title><m>\S VIII.6</m>: The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Motivation: The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We've conceptually defined definite integrals, but practically they're hard to compute. We'll make 
                            a connection to previous ideas that makes this easier.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>Example: Motivating the FTC</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>v(t)= -32t + 16</m> be the velocity of an object at time <m>t</m>. If the object's initial position is <m>32</m> feet,
                            what is the displacement
                            of the object from <m>t=0</m> to <m>t=2</m>?
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            There are two approaches we could take to answering this question. The first would be to find
                            the position function <m>s(t)</m> (i.e., the antiderivative satisfying the initial condition), and then
                            compute <m>s(2)-s(0)</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The second would be to graph <m>v(t)=s'(t)</m>, and find the signed area between <m>v(t)</m> and the input axis between
                            <m>t=0</m> and <m>t=2</m>. That is, compute <m>\displaystyle \int_0^2 v(t) \quad dt</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            These approaches compute the same thing. In symbols,
                            <me>
                                \displaystyle \int_0^2 s'(t) \quad dt = s(2) - s(0)
                            </me>,
                            which illustrates the important relationship described by the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus.
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="3in">
                    <title>The FTC</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>f(x)</m> be a continuous function on <m>[a,b]</m>, and <m>F(x)</m> an antiderivative of 
                            <m>f(x)</m>. Then
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                \int_a^b f(x) \quad dx = F(b) - F(a)
                            </me>.
                            It is common to notate <m>F(b) - F(a)</m> as <m>F(x)\Big|_a^b</m>
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace="3in">
                    <title>Example: The FTC</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle \int_0^1 x^2 \quad dx</m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <m>= \frac{1}{3}x^3\Big|_0^1 = \frac{1}{3}(1)^3 - \frac{1}{3}(0)^3 = \frac{1}{3}</m>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>
