            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Example: The FTC and Substitution</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle \int_1^2 x e^{x^2} \quad dx</m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Letting <m>u= x^2</m>, we obtain and solve the following definite integral with respect to <m>u</m>:
                            <me>
                                \int_1^4 0.5 e^u \quad du = 0.5e^u \Big|_1^4 = 0.5e^4 - 0.5e
                            </me>.

                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise>
                    <title>Practice: The FTC and Substitution</title>
                    <task workspace="3in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle \int_{1}^{2} \frac{x}{1+4x^2} \quad dx</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                Letting <m>u=1+4x^2</m>, we convert this definite integral to
                                <me>
                                    \int_5^{17} \frac{1}{8u} \quad du = \frac{1}{8}\ln|u| \Big|_5^{17} = \frac{1}{8}\ln(17) -\frac{1}{8}\ln(5)
                                </me>
                                
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="3in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle \int_{2/pi}^{4/\pi} \frac{\cos\left(\frac{1}{x}\right)}{x^2} \quad dx</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                Letting <m>u=x^{-1}</m>, we convert this definite integral to
                                <me>
                                    \int_{\pi/2}^{\pi/4} -\cos(u) \quad du = -\sin(u)\Big|_{\pi/2}^{\pi/4} = -\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}+1
                                </me>
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Interpreting Integrals with the FTC</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <image source="total-change.jpeg" width="50%">
                                <shortdescription>Graph of rate function in gallons per day with respect to time (in days), with
                                    the area accumulated between day 4 and 10 shaded.
                                </shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            The FTC tells us how to interpret a definite integral when the function we're integrating has
                            units. For example, if <m>r(t)</m> has units gallons per day and <m>R(t)</m> is an antiderivative
                            of <m>r</m>, then <m>R(t)</m> will have units of gallons. This tells us that an integral like
                            <m>\displaystyle \int_4^{10} r(t) \quad dt</m> tells us about the total change in gallons from day 4 
                            to day 10.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

